# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transport-layer-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] A **cipher suite** is a set of algorithms that help secure a network connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Suites typically use Transport Layer Security (TLS) or its deprecated predecessor Secure Socket Layer (SSL) as their protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The set of algorithms that cipher suites usually contain include: a key exchange algorithm, a bulk encryption algorithm, and a message authentication code (MAC) algorithm.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The key exchange algorithm is used to exchange a key between two devices.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] This key is used to encrypt and decrypt the messages being sent between two machines.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The bulk encryption algorithm is used to encrypt the data being sent.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The MAC algorithm provides data integrity checks to ensure that the data sent does not change in transit.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] In addition, cipher suites can include signatures and an authentication algorithm to help authenticate the server and or client.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Overall, there are hundreds of different cipher suites that contain different combinations of these algorithms.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Some cipher suites offer better security than others.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] But with the adoption of TLS 1.3, only 5 cipher suites have been officially supported and defined.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The structure and use of the cipher suite concept are defined in the TLS standard document.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] TLS 1.2 is the most prevalent version of TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The newest version of TLS (TLS 1.3) includes additional requirements to cipher suites.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Cipher suites defined for TLS 1.2 cannot be used in TLS 1.3, and vice versa, unless otherwise stated in their definition.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] A reference list of named cipher suites is provided in the TLS Cipher Suite Registry.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The use of ciphers has been a part of the Secure Socket Layer (SSL) transit protocol since its creation.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] SSL has been succeeded by TLS for most uses.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] However, the name *Cipher Suite* was not used in the original draft of SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Instead the ability for a client and a server to choose from a small set of ciphers to secure their connection was called *Cipher-Choice.* It was not until SSL v3 (the last version of SSL) that the name *Cipher Suite* was used.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Every version of TLS since has used *Cipher Suite* in its standardization.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The concept and purpose of a *Cipher Suite* has not changed since the term was first coined.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] It has and still is used as a structure describing the algorithms that a machine supports in order for two machines to decide which algorithms to use to secure their connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] What has changed is the versions of the algorithms that are supported in the cipher suites.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Each version of TLS has added support for stronger versions of the algorithms and removed support for versions of the algorithms that have been identified as insecure.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] TLS 1.3 marks a change in how cipher suites are coordinated between machines.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The cipher suite chosen for two communicating machines to use is determined by the handshake process.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Modifications were done in TLS 1.3 to the handshake process to cut down on the number of messages needed to be sent.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] This allows for less processing, less packet traffic and more efficiency compared to previous versions of TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Each cipher suite has a unique name that is used to identify it and to describe the algorithmic contents of it.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Each segment in a cipher suite name stands for a different algorithm or protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] defines the protocol that this cipher suite is for; it will usually be TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] authentication mechanism during the handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] type of encryption (cipher-block dependency and additional options).
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] which is used to authenticate a message.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] As of TLS 1.3 cipher suite names no longer include a certificate type (RSA) or key exchange mechanism (ECDHE), as these are negotiated separately in the new version.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] To use cipher suites, the client and the server must agree on the specific cipher suite that is going to be used in exchanging messages.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Both the client and the server must support the agreed upon cipher suite.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] If the client and server do not agree on a cipher suite, no connection will be made.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] This selection process occurs during the TLS Handshake Protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] TLS 1.3 includes a TLS Handshake Protocol that differs compared to past and the current version of TLS/SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] After coordinating which cipher suite to use, the server and the client still have the ability to change the coordinated ciphers by using the *ChangeCipherSpec* protocol in the current handshake or in a new handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] To test which TLS ciphers a server supports, an SSL/TLS Scanner may be used.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] This client starts the process by sending a *clientHello* message to the server that includes the version of TLS being used and a cipher suites list in the order of the client's preference.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] In response, the server sends a *serverHello* message that includes the chosen cipher suite and the session ID.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Next the server sends a digital certificate to verify its identity to the client.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The server may also request a client's digital certification if needed.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] If the client and server are not using pre-shared keys, the client then sends an encrypted message to the server that enables the client and the server to compute which secret key will be used during exchanges.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] If the *prefer server cipher* bit of *serverHello* message is set to true, the negotiated cipher suite is preferred on the cipher suites list of *serverHello* message; otherwise, the negotiated cipher suite is preferred on the cipher suites list of *clientHello* message.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] After successfully verifying the authentication of the server and, if needed, exchanging the secret key, the client sends a *finished* message to signal that it is done with the handshake process.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] After receiving this message, the server sends a *finished* message that confirms that the handshake is complete.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Now the client and the server are in agreement on which cipher suite to use to communicate with each other.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] If two machines are corresponding over TLS 1.3, they coordinate which cipher suite to use by using the TLS 1.3 Handshake Protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The handshake in TLS 1.3 was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] First the client sends a *clientHello* message to the server that contains a list of supported ciphers in order of the client's preference and makes a guess on what key algorithm is being used so that it can send a secret key to share if needed.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] By making a guess on what key algorithm that is being used it eliminates a round trip.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] After receiving the *clientHello*, the server sends a *serverHello* with its key, a certificate, the chosen cipher suite and the *finished* message.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] After the client receives the server's *finished* message it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] In TLS 1.3, many legacy algorithms that were supported in early versions of TLS have been dropped in an effort to make the protocol more secure.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] In addition, all encryption and authentication algorithms are combined in the authenticated encryption with associated data (AEAD) encryption algorithm.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Also a hash algorithm must now be used in HMAC-based key derivation (HKDF).
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] All non-AEAD ciphers have been removed due to possible weaknesses or vulnerabilities and ciphers must use an ephemeral key exchange algorithm so that new key pairs are generated for every exchange.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is based on TLS, but is specifically used for UDP connections instead of TCP connections.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Since DTLS is based on TLS it is able to use a majority of the cipher suites described for TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] There are special cases that must be considered when using TLS cipher suites with DTLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] DTLS does not support the stream cipher RC4 which means no TLS cipher suite using RC4 can be used with DTLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] To determine if a TLS cipher suite is compatible with DTLS looking at its name will not help.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Each TLS cipher suite will still include the TLS identifier space in its name. e.g.: *TLS_ECDHE_RSA_WITH_AES_128_GCM_SHA256*.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Instead, all TLS parameter registries now include the flag DTLS-OK to signal if a cipher suite supports DTLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] A cipher suite is as secure as the algorithms that it contains.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] If the version of encryption or authentication algorithm in a cipher suite have known vulnerabilities the cipher suite and TLS connection may then be vulnerable.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Therefore, a common attack against TLS and cipher suites is known as a downgrade attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] A downgrade in TLS occurs when a modern client connects to legacy servers that are using older versions of TLS or SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] When initiating a handshake, the modern client will offer the highest protocol that it supports.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] If the connection fails, it will automatically retry again with a lower protocol such as TLS 1.0 or SSL 3.0 until the handshake is successful with the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The purpose of downgrading is so that new versions of TLS are compatible with older versions.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] However, it is possible for an adversary to take advantage of this feature and make it so that a client will automatically downgrade to a version of TLS or SSL that supports cipher suites with algorithms that are known for weak security and vulnerabilities.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] This has resulted in attacks such as POODLE.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] One way to avoid this security flaw is to disable the ability of a server or client to be able to downgrade to SSL 3.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The shortcoming with this fix is that some legacy hardware cannot be accessed by newer hardware.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] If SSL 3.0 support is needed for legacy hardware, there is an approved TLS_FALLBACK_SCSV cipher suite which verifies that downgrades are not triggered for malicious intentions.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Encryption, key exchange and authentication algorithms usually require a large amount of processing power and memory.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] To provide security to constrained devices with limited processing power, memory, and battery life such as those powering the Internet of things there are specifically chosen cipher suites.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Each of these cipher suites has been implemented to run on devices with constraints in processing power and memory.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] They are both implemented in the open-sourced project TinyDTLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] The reason that they are able to work on these constrained devices is because they can be implemented in a light-weight fashion.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] Implementations of the pre-shared key cipher suite used only 1889 bytes of RAM and 38266 of flash ROM which is very resource-conscious compared to most encryption and security algorithms.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] This low memory usage is due to these cipher suites using proven efficient algorithms that are secure, but maybe not as secure as more resource-required algorithms; exp: Using 128 bit encryption vs 256 bit encryption.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] In addition they use pre-shared key or **raw** public key which requires less memory space and processing power compared to using traditional public key infrastructure (PKIX).
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] In programming, a cipher suite is referred to in both plural and non-plural forms.
[src:transport-layer-security/cipher-suite] a list of the cryptographic options supported by the client.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS Policy is communicated by the server to the user agent via an HTTP response header field named `Strict-Transport-Security`.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS Policy specifies a period of time during which the user agent should only access the server in a secure fashion.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Websites using HSTS often do not accept clear text HTTP, either by rejecting connections over HTTP or systematically redirecting users to HTTPS (though this is not required by the specification).
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The consequence of this is that a user-agent not capable of doing TLS will not be able to connect to the site.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The protection normally only applies after a user has visited the site at least once, relying on the principle of "trust on first use".
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The way this protection works is that when a user entering or selecting an HTTP (not HTTPS) URL to the site, the client, such as a Web browser, will automatically upgrade to HTTPS without making an HTTP request, thereby preventing any HTTP man-in-the-middle attack from occurring.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] To counteract this problem, an HSTS preload list maintained by Google Chrome and used by other major web browsers is maintained.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] If a domain is on this list, the browser skips the initial request and encrypts all communication immediately.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Additional domains can be registered at no cost.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS specification was published as RFC 6797 on 19 November 2012 after being approved on 2 October 2012 by the IESG for publication as a Proposed Standard RFC.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The authors originally submitted it as an Internet Draft on 17 June 2010.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] With the conversion to an Internet Draft, the specification name was altered from "Strict Transport Security" (STS) to "HTTP Strict Transport Security", because the specification applies only to HTTP.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HTTP response header field defined in the HSTS specification however remains named "Strict-Transport-Security".
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The last so-called "community version" of the then-named "STS" specification was published on 18 December 2009, with revisions based on community feedback.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The original draft specification by Jeff Hodges from PayPal, Collin Jackson, and Adam Barth was published on 18 September 2009.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS specification is based on original work by Jackson and Barth as described in their paper "ForceHTTPS: Protecting High-Security Web Sites from Network Attacks".
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Additionally, HSTS is the realization of one facet of an overall vision for improving web security, put forward by Jeff Hodges and Andy Steingruebl in their 2010 paper *The Need for Coherent Web Security Policy Framework(s)*.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] A server implements an HSTS policy by supplying a header over an HTTPS connection (HSTS headers over HTTP are ignored).
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] For example, a server could send a header such that future requests to the domain for the next year (max-age is specified in seconds; 31,536,000 is equal to one non-leap year) use only HTTPS: `Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000`.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] If the security of the connection cannot be ensured (e.g. the server's TLS certificate is not trusted), the user agent must terminate the connection and should not allow the user to access the web application.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] This helps protect web application users against some passive (eavesdropping) and active network attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] A man-in-the-middle attacker has a greatly reduced ability to intercept requests and responses between a user and a web application server while the user's browser has HSTS Policy in effect for that web application.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The most important security vulnerability that HSTS can fix is SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, first publicly introduced by Moxie Marlinspike in his 2009 BlackHat Federal talk "New Tricks For Defeating SSL In Practice".
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The SSL (and TLS) stripping attack works by transparently converting a secure HTTPS connection into a plain HTTP connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The user can see that the connection is insecure, but crucially there is no way of knowing whether the connection *should* be secure.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] At the time of Marlinspike's talk, many websites did not use TLS/SSL, therefore there was no way of knowing (without prior knowledge) whether the use of plain HTTP was due to an attack, or simply because the website had not implemented TLS/SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Additionally, no warnings are presented to the user during the downgrade process, making the attack fairly subtle to all but the most vigilant.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Marlinspike's sslstrip tool, presented at Black Hat DC 2009, fully automates the attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS addresses this problem by informing the browser that connections to the site should always use TLS/SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS header can be stripped by the attacker if this is the user's first visit.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Microsoft Edge attempt to limit this problem by including a "pre-loaded" list of HSTS sites.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Unfortunately this solution cannot scale to include all websites on the internet.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS can also help to prevent having one's cookie-based website login credentials stolen by widely available tools such as Firesheep.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Because HSTS is time limited, it is sensitive to attacks involving shifting the victim's computer time e.g. using false NTP packets.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The initial request remains unprotected from active attacks if it uses an insecure protocol such as plain HTTP or if the URI for the initial request was obtained over an insecure channel.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] The same applies to the first request after the activity period specified in the advertised HSTS Policy `max-age` (sites should set a period of several days or months depending on user activity and behavior).
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, and Internet Explorer/Microsoft Edge address this limitation by implementing a "HSTS preloaded list", which is a list that contains known sites supporting HSTS.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] This list is distributed with the browser so that it uses HTTPS for the initial request to the listed sites as well.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] As previously mentioned, these pre-loaded lists cannot scale to cover the entire Web.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] A potential solution might be achieved by using DNS records to declare HSTS Policy, and accessing them securely via DNSSEC, optionally with certificate fingerprints to ensure validity (which requires running a validating resolver to avoid last mile issues).
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Even with an HSTS preloaded list, HSTS cannot prevent advanced attacks against TLS itself, such as the BEAST or CRIME attacks introduced by Juliano Rizzo and Thai Duong.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Attacks against TLS itself are orthogonal to HSTS policy enforcement.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Neither can it protect against attacks on the server - if someone compromises it, it will happily serve any content over TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS can be used to near-indelibly tag visiting browsers with recoverable identifying data (supercookies) which can persist in and out of browser "incognito" privacy modes.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] By creating a web page that makes multiple HTTP requests to selected domains, for example, if twenty browser requests to twenty different domains are used, theoretically over one million visitors can be distinguished (220) due to the resulting requests arriving via HTTP vs.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] HTTPS; the latter being the previously recorded binary "bits" established earlier via HSTS headers.
[src:transport-layer-security/http-strict-transport-security] Depending on the actual deployment there are certain threats (e.g. cookie injection attacks) that can be avoided by following best practices.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The principal motivations for HTTPS are authentication of the accessed website and protection of the privacy and integrity of the exchanged data while it is in transit.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] It protects against man-in-the-middle attacks, and the bidirectional block cipher encryption of communications between a client and server protects the communications against eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The authentication aspect of HTTPS requires a trusted third party to sign server-side digital certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This was historically an expensive operation, which meant fully authenticated HTTPS connections were usually found only on secured payment transaction services and other secured corporate information systems on the World Wide Web.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] In 2016, a campaign by the Electronic Frontier Foundation with the support of web browser developers led to the protocol becoming more prevalent.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS has since 2018 been used more often by web users than non-secure HTTP, primarily to protect page authenticity on all types of websites, secure accounts, and keep user communications, identity, and web browsing private.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) scheme *HTTPS* has identical usage syntax to the HTTP scheme.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] However, HTTPS signals the browser to use an added encryption layer of SSL/TLS to protect the traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] SSL/TLS is especially suited for HTTP, since it can provide some protection even if only one side of the communication is authenticated.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This is the case with HTTP transactions over the Internet, where typically only the server is authenticated (by the client examining the server's certificate).
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS creates a secure channel over an insecure network.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This ensures reasonable protection from eavesdroppers and man-in-the-middle attacks, provided that adequate cipher suites are used and that the server certificate is verified and trusted.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Because HTTPS piggybacks HTTP entirely on top of TLS, the entirety of the underlying HTTP protocol can be encrypted.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This includes the request's URL, query parameters, headers, and cookies (which often contain identifying information about the user).
[src:transport-layer-security/https] However, because website addresses and port numbers are necessarily part of the underlying TCP/IP protocols, HTTPS cannot protect their disclosure.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Web browsers know how to trust HTTPS websites based on certificate authorities that come pre-installed in their software.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Certificate authorities are in this way being trusted by web browser creators to provide valid certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS is especially important over insecure networks and networks that may be subject to tampering.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Insecure networks, such as public Wi-Fi access points, allow anyone on the same local network to packet-sniff and discover sensitive information not protected by HTTPS.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Additionally, some free-to-use and paid WLAN networks have been observed tampering with webpages by engaging in packet injection in order to serve their own ads on other websites.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This practice can be exploited maliciously in many ways, such as by injecting malware onto webpages and stealing users' private information.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS is also important for connections over the Tor network, as malicious Tor nodes could otherwise damage or alter the contents passing through them in an insecure fashion and inject malware into the connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This is one reason why the Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Tor Project started the development of HTTPS Everywhere, which is included in Tor Browser.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] As more information is revealed about global mass surveillance and criminals stealing personal information, the use of HTTPS security on all websites is becoming increasingly important regardless of the type of Internet connection being used.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Even though metadata about individual pages that a user visits might not be considered sensitive, when aggregated it can reveal a lot about the user and compromise the user's privacy.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Deploying HTTPS also allows the use of HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 (and their predecessors SPDY and QUIC), which are new HTTP versions designed to reduce page load times, size, and latency.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] It is recommended to use HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) with HTTPS to protect users from man-in-the-middle attacks, especially SSL stripping.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS should not be confused with the seldom-used Secure HTTP (S-HTTP) specified in RFC 2660.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] As of April 2018, 33.2% of Alexa top 1,000,000 websites use HTTPS as default and 70% of page loads (measured by Firefox Telemetry) use HTTPS.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] As of June 2025, 71.2% of the Internet's 150,000 most popular websites have a secure implementation of HTTPS (up from 58.4% in December 2022), However, despite TLS 1.3's release in 2018, adoption has been slow, with many still remaining on the older TLS 1.2 protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Most browsers display a warning if they receive an invalid certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Older browsers, when connecting to a site with an invalid certificate, would present the user with a dialog box asking whether they wanted to continue.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Newer browsers display a warning across the entire window.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Newer browsers also prominently display the site's security information in the address bar.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Extended validation certificates show the legal entity on the certificate information.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Most browsers also display a warning to the user when visiting a site that contains a mixture of encrypted and unencrypted content.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Additionally, many web filters return a security warning when visiting prohibited websites.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, opining that "In an ideal world, every web request could be defaulted to HTTPS", has provided an add-on called HTTPS Everywhere for Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Chromium, and Android, which enables HTTPS by default for hundreds of frequently used websites.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Forcing a web browser to load only HTTPS content has been supported in Firefox starting in version 83.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Starting in version 94, Google Chrome is able to "always use secure connections" if toggled in the browser's settings.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Prior to version 117, Google Chrome displayed a lock icon in the address bar, which has since been replaced by a "tune" icon.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Many users believe that a lock icon implies a website is safe, ignoring other security concerns.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The security of HTTPS is that of the underlying TLS, which typically uses long-term public and private keys to generate a short-term session key, which is then used to encrypt the data flow between the client and the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] X.509 certificates are used to authenticate the server (and sometimes the client as well).
[src:transport-layer-security/https] As a consequence, certificate authorities and public key certificates are necessary to verify the relation between the certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] While this can be more beneficial than verifying the identities via a web of trust, the 2013 mass surveillance disclosures drew attention to certificate authorities as a potential weak point allowing man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] An important property in this context is forward secrecy, which ensures that encrypted communications recorded in the past cannot be retrieved and decrypted should long-term secret keys or passwords be compromised in the future.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Not all web servers provide forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] For HTTPS to be effective, a site must be completely hosted over HTTPS.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Additionally, cookies on a site served through HTTPS must have the secure attribute enabled.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] On a site that has sensitive information on it, the user and the session will get exposed every time that site is accessed with HTTP instead of HTTPS.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS URLs begin with "https://" and use port 443 by default, whereas HTTP URLs begin with "http://" and use port 80 by default.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTP is not encrypted and thus is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle and eavesdropping attacks, which can let attackers gain access to website accounts and sensitive information, and modify webpages to inject malware or advertisements.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS is designed to withstand such attacks and is considered secure against them (with the exception of HTTPS implementations that use deprecated versions of SSL).
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTP operates at the highest layer of the TCP/IP model—the application layer; as does the TLS security protocol (operating as a lower sublayer of the same layer), which encrypts an HTTP message prior to transmission and decrypts a message upon arrival.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Strictly speaking, HTTPS is not a separate protocol, but refers to the use of ordinary HTTP over an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS encrypts all message contents, including the HTTP headers and the request/response data.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] With the exception of the possible CCA cryptographic attack described in the limitations section below, an attacker should at most be able to discover that a connection is taking place between two parties, along with their domain names and IP addresses.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] To prepare a web server to accept HTTPS connections, the administrator must create a public key certificate for the web server.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This certificate must be signed by a trusted certificate authority for the web browser to accept it without warning.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The authority certifies that the certificate holder is the operator of the web server that presents it.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Web browsers are generally distributed with a list of signing certificates of major certificate authorities so that they can verify certificates signed by them.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] A number of commercial certificate authorities exist, offering paid-for SSL/TLS certificates of a number of types, including Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Let's Encrypt, launched in April 2016, provides free and automated service that delivers basic SSL/TLS certificates to websites.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Let's Encrypt will make switching from HTTP to HTTPS "as easy as issuing one command, or clicking one button." The majority of web hosts and cloud providers now leverage Let's Encrypt, providing free certificates to their customers.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The system can also be used for client authentication in order to limit access to a web server to authorized users.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] To do this, the site administrator typically creates a certificate for each user, which the user loads into their browser.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Normally, the certificate contains the name and e-mail address of the authorized user and is automatically checked by the server on each connection to verify the user's identity, potentially without even requiring a password.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] An important property in this context is perfect forward secrecy (PFS).
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Possessing one of the long-term asymmetric secret keys used to establish an HTTPS session should not make it easier to derive the short-term session key to then decrypt the conversation, even at a later time.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Diffie–Hellman key exchange (DHE) and Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman key exchange (ECDHE) are in 2013 the only schemes known to have that property.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] In 2013, only 30% of Firefox, Opera, and Chromium Browser sessions used it, and nearly 0% of Apple's Safari and Microsoft Internet Explorer sessions.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] TLS 1.3, published in August 2018, dropped support for ciphers without forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] As of February 2019, 96.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 52.1% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] As of July 2023, 99.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 75.2% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, for example because the secrecy of the private key has been compromised.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Newer versions of popular browsers such as Firefox, Opera, and Internet Explorer on Windows Vista implement the Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) to verify that this is not the case.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The browser sends the certificate's serial number to the certificate authority or its delegate via OCSP (Online Certificate Status Protocol) and the authority responds, telling the browser whether the certificate is still valid or not.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The CA may also issue a CRL to tell people that these certificates are revoked.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] CRLs are no longer required by the CA/Browser forum, nevertheless, they are still widely used by the CAs.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Most revocation statuses on the Internet disappear soon after the expiration of the certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security) encryption can be configured in two modes: *simple* and *mutual*.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] In simple mode, authentication is only performed by the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The mutual version requires the user to install a personal client certificate in the web browser for user authentication.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] In either case, the level of protection depends on the correctness of the implementation of the software and the cryptographic algorithms in use.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] SSL/TLS does not prevent the indexing of the site by a web crawler, and in some cases the URI of the encrypted resource can be inferred by knowing only the intercepted request/response size.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This allows an attacker to have access to the plaintext (the publicly available static content), and the encrypted text (the encrypted version of the static content), permitting a cryptographic attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Because TLS operates at a protocol level below that of HTTP and has no knowledge of the higher-level protocols, TLS servers can only strictly present one certificate for a particular address and port combination.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] In the past, this meant that it was not feasible to use name-based virtual hosting with HTTPS.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] A solution called Server Name Indication (SNI) exists, which sends the hostname to the server before encrypting the connection, although older browsers do not support this extension.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Support for SNI is available since Firefox 2, Opera 8, Apple Safari 2.1, Google Chrome 6, and Internet Explorer 7 on Windows Vista.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] A sophisticated type of man-in-the-middle attack called SSL stripping was presented at the 2009 Blackhat Conference.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The attacker then communicates in clear with the client.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This prompted the development of a countermeasure in HTTP called HTTP Strict Transport Security.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] HTTPS has been shown to be vulnerable to a range of traffic analysis attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Traffic analysis attacks are a type of side-channel attack that relies on variations in the timing and size of traffic in order to infer properties about the encrypted traffic itself.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Traffic analysis is possible because SSL/TLS encryption changes the contents of traffic, but has minimal impact on the size and timing of traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] In May 2010, a research paper by researchers from Microsoft Research and Indiana University discovered that detailed sensitive user data can be inferred from side channels such as packet sizes.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The researchers found that, despite HTTPS protection in several high-profile, top-of-the-line web applications in healthcare, taxation, investment, and web search, an eavesdropper could infer the illnesses/medications/surgeries of the user, his/her family income, and investment secrets.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The fact that most modern websites, including Google, Yahoo!, and Amazon, use HTTPS causes problems for many users trying to access public Wi-Fi hot spots, because a captive portal Wi-Fi hot spot login page fails to load if the user tries to open an HTTPS resource.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Several websites, such as NoSSL.sh, guarantee that they will always remain accessible by HTTP.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Netscape Communications created HTTPS in 1994 for its Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Originally, HTTPS was used with the SSL protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] The original SSL protocol was developed by Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] As SSL evolved into Transport Layer Security (TLS), HTTPS was formally specified by RFC 2818 in May 2000.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] Google announced in February 2018 that its Chrome browser would mark HTTP sites as "Not Secure" after July 2018.
[src:transport-layer-security/https] This move was to encourage website owners to implement HTTPS, as an effort to make the World Wide Web more secure.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] For TLS, the long-term secret is typically the private key of the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy protects past sessions against future compromises of keys or passwords.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] By generating a unique session key for every session a user initiates, the compromise of a single session key will not affect any data other than that exchanged in the specific session protected by that particular key.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] This by itself is not sufficient for forward secrecy, which additionally requires that a long-term secret compromise does not affect the security of past session keys.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy protects data on the transport layer of a network that uses common transport layer security protocols, including OpenSSL, when its long-term secret keys are compromised, as with the Heartbleed security bug.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] If forward secrecy is used, encrypted communications and sessions recorded in the past cannot be retrieved and decrypted should long-term secret keys or passwords be compromised in the future, even if the adversary actively interfered, for example via a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] The value of forward secrecy is that it protects past communication.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] This reduces the motivation for attackers to compromise keys.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] For instance, if an attacker learns a long-term key, but the compromise is detected and the long-term key is revoked and updated, relatively little information is leaked in a forward secure system.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] The value of forward secrecy depends on the assumed capabilities of an adversary.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy has value if an adversary is assumed to be able to obtain secret keys from a device (read access) but is either detected or unable to modify the way session keys are generated in the device (full compromise).
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] In some cases an adversary who can read long-term keys from a device may also be able to modify the functioning of the session key generator, as in the backdoored Dual Elliptic Curve Deterministic Random Bit Generator.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] If an adversary can make the random number generator predictable, then past traffic will be protected but all future traffic will be compromised.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy typically uses an ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to prevent reading past traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] The ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange is often signed by the server using a static signing key.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] If an adversary can steal (or obtain through a court order) this static (long term) signing key, the adversary can masquerade as the server to the client and as the client to the server and implement a classic man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] The term "perfect forward secrecy" was coined by C.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Günther in 1990 and further discussed by Whitfield Diffie, Paul van Oorschot, and Michael James Wiener in 1992, where it was used to describe a property of the Station-to-Station protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy has also been used to describe the analogous property of password-authenticated key agreement protocols where the long-term secret is a (shared) password.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] In 2000 the IEEE first ratified IEEE 1363, which establishes the related one-party and two-party forward secrecy properties of various standard key agreement schemes.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] An encryption system has the property of forward secrecy if plain-text (decrypted) inspection of the data exchange that occurs during key agreement phase of session initiation does not reveal the key that was used to encrypt the remainder of the session.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Alice and Bob use a key exchange algorithm such as Diffie–Hellman, to securely agree on an ephemeral session key.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] They use the keys from step 1 only to authenticate one another during this process.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Alice sends Bob a message, encrypting it with a symmetric cipher using the session key negotiated in step 2.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Bob decrypts Alice's message using the key negotiated in step 2.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] The process repeats for each new message sent, starting from step 2 (and switching Alice and Bob's roles as sender/receiver as appropriate).
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy (achieved by generating new session keys for each message) ensures that past communications cannot be decrypted if one of the keys generated in an iteration of step 2 is compromised, since such a key is only used to encrypt a single message.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy also ensures that past communications cannot be decrypted if the long-term private keys from step 1 are compromised.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] However, masquerading as Alice or Bob would be possible going forward if this occurred, possibly compromising all future messages.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy is designed to prevent the compromise of a long-term secret key from affecting the confidentiality of past conversations.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] However, forward secrecy cannot defend against a successful cryptanalysis of the underlying ciphers being used, since a cryptanalysis consists of finding a way to decrypt an encrypted message without the key, and forward secrecy only protects keys, not the ciphers themselves.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] This would allow the recovery of old plaintexts even in a system employing forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Non-interactive forward-secure key exchange protocols face additional threats that are not relevant to interactive protocols.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Proactively retiring private keys on a schedule mitigates, but does not eliminate, this attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] In a *malicious key exhaustion* attack, the attacker sends many messages to the recipient and exhausts the private key material, forcing a protocol to choose between failing closed (and enabling denial of service attacks) or failing open (and giving up some amount of forward secrecy).
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Most key exchange protocols are *interactive*, requiring bidirectional communication between the parties.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] A protocol that permits the sender to transmit data without first needing to receive any replies from the recipient may be called *non-interactive*, or *asynchronous*, or *zero round-trip time* (0-RTT).
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] These use cases have stimulated interest in non-interactive key exchange, and, as forward security is a desirable property in a key-exchange protocol, in non-interactive forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] This combination has been identified as desirable since at least 1996.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] However, combining forward secrecy and non-interactivity has proven challenging; it had been suspected that forward secrecy with protection against replay attacks was impossible non-interactively, but it has been shown to be possible to achieve all three desiderata.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Broadly, two approaches to non-interactive forward secrecy have been explored, *pre-computed keys* and *puncturable encryption*.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] With pre-computed keys, many key pairs are created and the public keys shared, with the private keys destroyed after a message has been received using the corresponding public key.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] This approach has been deployed as part of the Signal protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] In puncturable encryption, the recipient modifies their private key after receiving a message in such a way that the new private key cannot read the message but the public key is unchanged.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Green & Miers (2015) make use of hierarchical identity-based encryption and attribute-based encryption, while Günther et al.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] (2017) use a different construction that can be based on any hierarchical identity-based scheme.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] (2020) experimentally found that modifying QUIC to use a 0-RTT forward secure and replay-resistant key exchange implemented with puncturable encryption incurred significantly increased resource usage, but not so much as to make practical use infeasible.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Weak perfect forward secrecy (Wpfs) is the weaker property whereby when agents' long-term keys are compromised, the secrecy of previously established session keys is guaranteed, but only for sessions in which the adversary did not actively interfere.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] This new notion, and the distinction between this and forward secrecy, was introduced by Hugo Krawczyk in 2005.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] This weaker definition implicitly requires that full (perfect) forward secrecy maintains the secrecy of previously established session keys even in sessions where the adversary *did* actively interfere or attempted to act as a man in the middle.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy is present in several protocol implementations, such as SSH and IPsec (RFC 2412), though it is optional in the latter.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Off-the-Record Messaging, a cryptography protocol and library for many instant messaging clients, as well as OMEMO which provides additional features such as multi-user functionality in such clients, both provide forward secrecy as well as deniable encryption.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] In Transport Layer Security (TLS), cipher suites based on Diffie–Hellman key exchange (DHE-RSA, DHE-DSA) and elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman key exchange (ECDHE-RSA, ECDHE-ECDSA) are available.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] In theory, TLS can use forward secrecy since SSLv3, but many implementations do not offer forward secrecy or provided it with lower-grade encryption.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] TLS 1.3 removed support for RSA for key exchange, leaving Diffie–Hellman (with forward secrecy) as the sole algorithm for key exchange.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] OpenSSL supports forward secrecy using elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman since version 1.0, with a computational overhead of approximately 15% for the initial handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] The Signal Protocol uses the Double Ratchet Algorithm to provide forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] On the other hand, among popular protocols currently in use, WPA Personal did not support forward secrecy before WPA3.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Since late 2011, Google provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, Google Docs service, and encrypted search services.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Since November 2013, Twitter provided forward secrecy with TLS to its users.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Wikis hosted by the Wikimedia Foundation have all provided forward secrecy to users since July 2014, and have required the use of forward secrecy since August 2018.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Facebook reported as part of an investigation into email encryption that, as of May 2014, 74% of hosts that support STARTTLS also provide forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] At WWDC 2016, Apple announced that all iOS apps would need to use App Transport Security (ATS), a feature which enforces the use of HTTPS transmission.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] Specifically, ATS requires the use of an encryption cipher that provides forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] ATS became mandatory for apps on January 1, 2017.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] The Signal messaging application employs forward secrecy in its protocol, notably differentiating it from messaging protocols based on PGP.
[src:transport-layer-security/perfect-forward-secrecy] In one survey in June 2025, forward secrecy was supported by about 95% of popular websites when accessed with modern browsers, while 0.2% did not support it at all.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Prior to SNI, when making a TLS connection, the client had no way to specify which site it was trying to connect to.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Hence, if one server hosts multiple sites on a single listener, the server has no way to know which certificate to use in the TLS protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In more detail, when making a TLS connection, the client requests a digital certificate from the web server.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Once the server sends the certificate, the client examines it and compares the name it was trying to connect to with the name(s) included in the certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] If a match occurs, the connection proceeds as normal.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] If a match is not found, the user may be warned of the discrepancy and the connection may abort as the mismatch may indicate an attempted man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] However, some applications allow the user to bypass the warning to proceed with the connection, with the user taking on the responsibility of trusting the certificate and, by extension, the connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] However, it may be hard – or even impossible due to lack of a full list of all names in advance – to obtain a single certificate that covers all names a server will be responsible for.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] A server that is responsible for multiple hostnames is likely to need to present a different certificate for each name (or small group of names).
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] It is possible to use *subjectAltName* to contain multiple domains controlled by one person in a single certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Such "unified communications certificates" must be reissued every time the list of domains changes.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Name-based virtual hosting allows multiple DNS hostnames to be hosted by a single server (usually a web server) on the same IP address.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] To achieve this, the server uses a hostname presented by the client as part of the protocol (for HTTP the name is presented in the host header).
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] However, when using HTTPS, the TLS handshake happens before the server sees any HTTP headers.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Therefore, it was not possible for the server to use the information in the HTTP host header to decide which certificate to present and as such only names covered by the same certificate could be served from the same IP address.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In practice, this meant that an HTTPS server could only serve one domain (or small group of domains) per IP address for secured and efficient browsing.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Assigning a separate IP address for each site increases the cost of hosting, since requests for IP addresses must be justified to the regional Internet registry and IPv4 addresses are now exhausted.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] For IPv6, it increases the administrative overhead by having multiple IPs on a single machine, even though the address space is not exhausted.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] The result was that many websites were effectively constrained from using secure communications.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] SNI addresses this issue by having the client send the name of the virtual domain as part of the TLS negotiation's *ClientHello* message.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] This enables the server to select the correct virtual domain early and present the browser with the certificate containing the correct name.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Therefore, with clients and servers that implement SNI, a server with a single IP address can serve a group of domain names for which it is impractical to get a common certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] SNI was added to the IETF's Internet RFCs in June 2003 through RFC 3546, *Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions*.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] The latest version of the standard is RFC 6066.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Server Name Indication payload is not encrypted, thus the hostname of the server the client tries to connect to is visible to a passive eavesdropper.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] This protocol weakness was exploited by security software for network filtering and monitoring and governments to implement censorship.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Domain fronting is a technique of replacing the desired host name in SNI with another one hosted by the same server or, more frequently, network of servers known as a content delivery network.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] When a client uses domain fronting, it replaces the server domain in SNI (unencrypted), but leaves it in the HTTP host header (which is encrypted by TLS) so that server can serve the right content.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Domain fronting violates the standard defining SNI itself, so its compatibility is limited (many services check that SNI host matches the HTTP header host and reject connections with domain-fronted SNI as invalid).
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] While domain fronting was used in the past to avoid government censorship, its popularity dwindled because major cloud providers (Google, Amazon's AWS and CloudFront) explicitly prohibit it in their TOS and have technical restrictions against it.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] The initial 2018 version of this extension was called Encrypted SNI (ESNI).
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In March 2020, ESNI was reworked into the ECH extension, after analysis demonstrated that encrypting only the SNI is insufficient.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] For example, specifications permit the Pre-Shared Key extension to contain any data to facilitate session resumption, even transmission of a cleartext copy of exactly the same server name that is encrypted by ESNI.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Also, encrypting extensions one-by-one would require an encrypted variant of every extension, each with potential privacy implications, and even that exposes the set of extensions advertised.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Lastly, real-world deployment of ESNI has exposed interoperability limitations.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] The short name was *ECHO* in March 2020 and changed to *ECH* in May 2020.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In July 2023, in the IETF117 meeting, members working on ECH informed Chrome and Firefox were doing a 1% sample trial, and the team expects the final draft to be submitted to the IESG evaluation by January 2024.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In September 2023, Cloudflare started to support ECH for hosted domains.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In September 2023, Chromium version 117 (used in Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Samsung Internet, and Opera) enabled ECH by default, also requiring keys to be deployed in HTTPS resource records in DNS.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] ECH is enabled in Firefox by default since version 119 released in October 2023, and is recommended by Mozilla to be used along with DNS over HTTPS.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In April 2026, OpenSSL 4.0 included support for ECH.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Since its December 2025 release, NGINX supports ECH with OpenSSL 4.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] The initial 2018 version of this extension was called Encrypted SNI (ESNI) and its implementations were rolled out in an "experimental" fashion to address this risk of domain eavesdropping.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In contrast to ECH, Encrypted SNI encrypted just the SNI rather than the whole Client Hello.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Opt-in support for this version was incorporated into Firefox in October 2018 and required enabling DNS over HTTPS (DoH).
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] But it was removed in January 2021 with the release of Firefox 85.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Both ESNI and ECH are compatible only with TLS 1.3 because they rely on KeyShareEntry which was first defined in TLS 1.3.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In August 2020, the Great Firewall of China started blocking ESNI traffic, while still allowing ECH traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In October 2020, Russian ISP Rostelecom and its mobile operator Tele2 started blocking ESNI traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In September of the same year, Russian censorship ministry Roscomnadzor planned to ban a range of encryption protocols, among which were TLS 1.3 and ESNI, which hindered web site access censorship.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In 2004, a patch for adding TLS/SNI into OpenSSL was created by the EdelKey project.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] In 2006, this patch was then ported to the development branch of OpenSSL, and in 2007 it was back-ported to OpenSSL 0.9.8 (first released in 0.9.8f).
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] First web browsers with SNI support appeared in 2006 (Mozilla Firefox 2.0, Internet Explorer 7), web servers later (Apache HTTP Server in 2009, Microsoft IIS in 2012).
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] For an application program to implement SNI, the TLS library it uses must implement it and the application must pass the hostname to the TLS library.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Further complicating matters, the TLS library may either be included in the application program or be a component of the underlying operating system.
[src:transport-layer-security/server-name-indication] Because of this, some browsers implement SNI when running on any operating system, while others implement it only when running on certain operating systems.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet provides guidance on implementing transport layer protection for applications using Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] It primarily focuses on how to use TLS to protect clients connecting to a web application over HTTPS, though much of this guidance is also applicable to other uses of TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Secure Socket Layer (SSL) was the original protocol that was used to provide encryption for HTTP traffic, in the form of HTTPS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] There were two publicly released versions of SSL - versions 2 and 3.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Both of these have serious cryptographic weaknesses and should no longer be used.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For various reasons the next version of the protocol (effectively SSL 3.1) was named Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Subsequently TLS versions 1.1, 1.2 and 1.3 have been released.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The terms "SSL", "SSL/TLS" and "TLS" are frequently used interchangeably, and in many cases "SSL" is used when referring to the more modern TLS protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet will use the term "TLS" except where referring to the legacy protocols.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Web applications must default to **TLS 1.3** and may support TLS 1.2 for compatibility.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] **TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1 are formally deprecated by RFC 8996 (March 2021) and must be disabled.** They are also forbidden by PCI DSS, disallowed by NIST SP 800-52 Rev.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] 2, and removed from all mainstream browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] SSLv2 and SSLv3 must always be disabled.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] If interoperability with end-of-life clients is a hard business requirement, isolate them on a dedicated endpoint with no access to sensitive data — do not weaken the primary endpoint.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The "TLS_FALLBACK_SCSV" extension should be enabled to prevent protocol downgrade attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] There are a large number of different ciphers (or cipher suites) that are supported by TLS, that provide varying levels of security.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For TLS 1.3, use the standard AEAD cipher suites (AES‑GCM or ChaCha20‑Poly1305).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] If TLS 1.2 is still required, prefer AEAD‑based suites there as well and avoid CBC‑mode ciphers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The Mozilla Foundation provides an easy-to-use secure configuration generator for web, database and mail servers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This tool allows site administrators to select the software they are using and receive a configuration file that is optimized to balance security and compatibility for a wide variety of browser versions and server software.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The practice of earlier than TLS 1.3 protocol versions of Diffie-Hellman parameter generation for use by the ephemeral Diffie-Hellman key exchange (signified by the "DHE" or "EDH" strings in the cipher suite name) had practical issues.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For example, the client had no say in the selection of server parameters, meaning it could only unconditionally accept or drop, and the random parameter generation often resulted to denial of service attacks (CVE-2022-40735, CVE-2002-20001).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For OpenSSL, the list of enabled groups can be configured ins in `openssl.cnf`.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For TLS 1.2 or earlier versions it is recommended not to set Diffie-Hellman parameters.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] TLS compression should be disabled in order to protect against a vulnerability (nicknamed CRIME) which could potentially allow sensitive information such as session cookies to be recovered by an attacker.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] As well as the vulnerabilities in the SSL and TLS protocols, there have also been a large number of historic vulnerability in SSL and TLS libraries, with Heartbleed being the most well known.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] As such, it is important to ensure that these libraries are kept up to date with the latest security patches.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Once the server has been hardened, the configuration should be tested.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The OWASP Testing Guide chapter on SSL/TLS Testing contains further information on testing.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The private key used to generate the cipher key must be sufficiently strong for the anticipated lifetime of the private key and corresponding certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The current best practice is to select a key size of at least 2048 bits when using RSA keys.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Additional information on key lifetimes and comparable key strengths can be found here and in NIST SP 800-57.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The private key should also be protected from unauthorized access using filesystem permissions and other technical and administrative controls.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Certificates should use SHA-256 for the hashing algorithm, rather than the older MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] These have a number of cryptographic weaknesses, and are not trusted by modern browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The domain name (or subject) of the certificate must match the fully qualified name of the server that presents the certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Historically this was stored in the `commonName` (CN) attribute of the certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] However, modern versions of Chrome ignore the CN attribute, and require that the FQDN is in the `subjectAlternativeName` (SAN) attribute.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For compatibility reasons, certificates should have the primary FQDN in the CN, and the full list of FQDNs in the SAN.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Wildcard certificates can be convenient, however they violate the principle of least privilege, as a single certificate is valid for all subdomains of a domain (such as *.example.org).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Where multiple systems are sharing a wildcard certificate, the likelihood that the private key for the certificate is compromised increases, as the key may be present on multiple systems.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Additionally, the value of this key is significantly increased, making it a more attractive target for attackers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The issues around the use of wildcard certificates are complicated, and there are various other discussions of them online.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] In order to be trusted by users, certificates must be signed by a trusted certificate authority (CA).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For Internet facing applications, this should be one of the CAs which are well-known and automatically trusted by operating systems and browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The LetsEncrypt CA provides free domain validated SSL certificates, which are trusted by all major browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] As such, consider whether there are any benefits to purchasing a certificate from a CA.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For internal applications, an internal CA can be used.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This means that the FQDN of the certificate will not be exposed (either to an external CA, or publicly in certificate transparency lists).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] However, the certificate will only be trusted by users who have imported and trusted the internal CA certificate that was used to sign them.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Certification Authority Authorization (CAA) DNS records can be used to define which CAs are permitted to issue certificates for a domain.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The records contains a list of CAs, and any CA who is not included in that list should refuse to issue a certificate for the domain.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This can help to prevent an attacker from obtaining unauthorized certificates for a domain through a less-reputable CA.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Where it is applied to all subdomains, it can also be useful from an administrative perspective by limiting which CAs administrators or developers are able to use, and by preventing them from obtaining unauthorized wildcard certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Certificates come in different types of validation.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Validation is the process the Certificate Authority (CA) uses to make sure you are allowed to have the certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The CA/Browser Forum is an organization made of CA and browser vendors, as well as others with an interest in web security.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] They set the rules which CAs must follow based on the validation type.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The base validation is called Domain Validated (DV).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] All publicly issued certificates must be domain validated.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This process involves practical proof of control of the name or endpoint requested in the certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This usually involves a challenge and response in DNS, to an official email address, or to the endpoint that will get the certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Organization Validated (OV) certificates include the requestor’s organization information in the certificates subject.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] C = GB, ST = Manchester, **O = Sectigo Limited**, CN = sectigo.com.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The process to acquire an OV certificate requires official contact with the requesting company via a method that proves to the CA that they are truly talking to the right company.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Extended validation (EV) certificates provide an even higher level of verification as well as all the DV and OV verifications.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This can effectively be viewed as the difference between "This site is really run by Example Company Inc." vs "This domain is really example.org".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Historically these displayed differently in the browser, often showing the company name or a green icon or background in the address bar.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] However, as of 2019 no major browser shows EV status like this as they do not believe that EV certificates provide any additional protection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] (Chromium Covering Chrome, Edge, Brave, and Opera.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] As all browsers and TLS stacks are unaware of the difference between DV, OV, and EV certificates, they are effectively the same in terms of security.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] An attacker only needs to reach the level of practical control of the domain to get a rogue certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The extra work for an attacker to get an OV or EV certificate in no way increases the scope of an incident.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] In fact, those actions would likely mean detection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The additional pain in getting OV and EV certificates may create an availability risk and their use should be reviewed with this in mind.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] TLS should be used for all pages, not just those that are considered sensitive such as the login page.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] If there are any pages that do not enforce the use of TLS, these could give an attacker an opportunity to sniff sensitive information such as session tokens, or to inject malicious JavaScript into the responses to carry out other attacks against the user.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] For public facing applications, it may be appropriate to have the web server listening for unencrypted HTTP connections on port 80, and then immediately redirecting them with a permanent redirect (HTTP 301) in order to provide a better experience to users who manually type in the domain name.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This should then be supported with the HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) header to prevent them accessing the site over HTTP in the future.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] API-only endpoints should disable HTTP altogether and only support encrypted connections.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] When that is not possible, API endpoints should fail requests made over unencrypted HTTP connections instead of redirecting them.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] A page that is available over TLS should not include any resources (such as JavaScript or CSS) files which are loaded over unencrypted HTTP.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] These unencrypted resources could allow an attacker to sniff session cookies or inject malicious code into the page.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Modern browsers will also block attempts to load active content over unencrypted HTTP into secure pages.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] All cookies should be marked with the "Secure" attribute, which instructs the browser to only send them over encrypted HTTPS connections, in order to prevent them from being sniffed from an unencrypted HTTP connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This is important even if the website does not listen on HTTP (port 80), as an attacker performing an active man in the middle attack could present a spoofed web server on port 80 to the user in order to steal their cookie.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Although TLS provides protection of data while it is in transit, it does not provide any protection for data once it has reached the requesting system.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] As such, this information may be stored in the cache of the user's browser, or by any intercepting proxies which are configured to perform TLS decryption.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Where sensitive data is returned in responses, HTTP headers should be used to instruct the browser and any proxy server not to cache the information, in order to prevent it being stored or returned to other users.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] `no-store` is the strongest cache directive: it forbids both shared and private caches from storing any part of the response.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The legacy combination `Cache-Control: no-cache, no-store, must-revalidate` plus `Pragma: no-cache` and `Expires: 0` is only required if you must support pre-HTTP/1.1 caches (effectively obsolete in 2024+) and adds no protection beyond `no-store` on a modern stack.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Note that `Cache-Control` governs the HTTP cache; it does not control whether the browser stores cookies in its cookie jar — that is controlled by the cookie attributes (`Max-Age`, `Expires`, `Session`).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] If you also need to clear data already cached on the client at sign-out, additionally send `Clear-Site-Data` (e.g.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) instructs the user's browser to always request the site over HTTPS, and also prevents the user from bypassing certificate warnings.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] See the HTTP Strict Transport Security Cheat Sheet for further information on implementing HSTS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] In a typical TLS configuration, a certificate on the server allows the client to verify the server's identity and provides an encrypted connection between them.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Client certificates, central to mutual TLS (mTLS), address these issues.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] In mTLS, both the client and server authenticate each other using TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] The client proves their identity to the server with their own certificate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This not only enables strong authentication of the client but also prevents an intermediate party from decrypting TLS traffic, even if they have a trusted CA certificate on the client system.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Despite these challenges, client certificates and mTLS should be considered for high-value applications or APIs, particularly where users are technically sophisticated or part of the same organization.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Public key pinning can be used to provides assurance that the server's certificate is not only valid and trusted, but also that it matches the certificate expected for the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This provides protection against an attacker who is able to obtain a valid certificate, either by exploiting a weakness in the validation process, compromising a trusted certificate authority, or having administrative access to the client.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] Public key pinning was added to browsers in the HTTP Public Key Pinning (HPKP) standard.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] However, due to a number of issues, it has subsequently been deprecated and is no longer recommended or supported by modern browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] However, public key pinning can still provide security benefits for mobile applications, thick clients and server-to-server communication.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-cheat-sheet] This is discussed in further detail in the Pinning Cheat Sheet.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:transport-layer-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
